@NODE "requirements" "Requirements"
@PREV "legalstuff"
@NEXT "howtouse"

@{b}@{u}Systemrequirements@{ub}@{uu}

An Amiga :-)

Kickstart 2.04 or higher

At least an MC68020
(If a lot are interested in a 68000er-Version, I'll make it.)

The @{"iff.library" link "ifflib"} respectively Datatypes (OS2.1+)
(By missing this both, backgroundloading is disabled.)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "howtouse" "How to use"
@PREV "requirements"
@NEXT "howtoconfig"

@{b}@{u}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

Using MagicClock is very easy. You can start it from the Workbench, by
a doubleclick on the MagicClock-icon or from the Shell.

If you start MagicClock from the Shell it starts an own process.
You should put MagicClock into the WBStartup-drawer if you want to use it
every time  ;-)).

The @{"configuration" link "howtoconfig"} of MagicClock uses menus.

How to use the window you can see in this little design:


                                           depthgadget
                                             /
                +-------------------------+---+
                |                         |   |
                |                         +---+
                |                         |   |
                |                         |   |
                |                         |   |
                |     draggadget          |   | - sizegadget
                |                         |   |   (horizontal)
                |                         |   |
                |                         |   |
                |                         |   |
                |                         |   |
                |-------------------------+---+
                |                         |   |
                +-------------------------+---+
                         |                   \\
                    sizegadget          sizegadget
                    (vertikal)           (every direction)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "howtoconfig" "Configuration"
@PREV "howtouse"
@NEXT "install"

MagicClock is easy to config by using the menu.
Some menupoints are described by short-cuts.

Here is the @{b}@{u}description@{ub}@{uu} for the menus:

@{" Project " link "project"} @{" Hands " link "hands"} @{" Display " link "display"} @{" Background " link "background"} @{" Border " link "border"} @{" Sound " link "sound"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "project" "Project"

With the @{b}@{u}Project-Menu@{ub}@{uu} you can make global adjustments

@{bg shine}Open Prefs...@{bg background}

Loads a saved preferencefile and resets settings.

@{bg shine}Save Prefs@{bg background}

Saves the actual settings to drawer 'envarc:MagicClock' with the name
'MagicClock.prefs'.

@{bg shine}Save Prefs As...@{bg background}

Saves the actual settings to a selectable path with a selectable name.

@{bg shine}Set Startdelay...@{bg background}

Sets the time the program waits before it starts. That's necessary
if you want to snap the background already when starting, but the background
needs a little longer to appear.

@{bg shine}About...@{bg background}

Shows informations about program and @{"authors" link "authors"}.

@{bg shine}Quit@{bg background}

Quits the program.
@ENDNODE

With this menu you can adjust the @{b}@{b}hands@{ub}@{uu} of the clock

@NODE "hands" "Hands"

@{" HourHand " link "hourhand"}
@{" MinHand  "  link "minhand"}
@{" SecHand  " link "sechand"}

@{bg shine}Second@{bg background}

Turns the secondhand on/off.

@{bg shine}Shadow Degree...@{bg background}

Sets the degree of the light in a range from 0-359.
(0 degree is above; the angle moved anticlockwise (sorry))

@{bg shine}Shadow Color...@{bg background}

Sets the shadowcolor (It`s the same for any shadow).

@{bg shine}Double Buffering@{bg background}

Turns the graphic buffering on/off.
Without doublebuffering it was drawn directly into the window. This saves
memory but it could flicker when a lot of points were drawn or big areas
must be filled. This can also happens if you use big windows and/or you
have a slow graphicoutput.
But is doublebuffering turned ON this affect will be stopped.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "hourhand" "HourHand"

                  Special settings for the @{b}@{u}Hourhand@{ub}@{uu}

@{bg shine}Open...@{bg background}

Loads a saved hourhand.

@{bg shine}Triangle@{bg background}

Sets the hourhand to the internal triangle-form.

@{bg shine}Rectangle@{bg background}

Sets the hourhand to the internal rectangle-form.

@{bg shine}Line@{bg background}

Sets the hourhand to the internal line-form.

@{bg shine}Transparent@{bg background}

Draws only the border of the hand.

@{bg shine}Fit To Nums@{bg background}

Fits the hand directly to the dail.
It's only useable for non-circle dails (Rectangle).

@{bg shine}FillColor...@{bg background}

Sets the color that fills the hand. Transparents has to be turned off.

@{bg shine}BorderColor...@{bg background}

Sets the color for the handborder.

@{bg shine}Shadow@{bg background}

Turns the shadow for the hourhand on/off.

@{bg shine}Shadow Depth...@{bg background}

Sets the shadowdepth for the shadow of the hourhand.
@ENDNODE

